# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: north-macedonia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] About 80 percent of the city was destroyed.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The earthquake, which measured 6.1 on the moment magnitude scale, occurred on July 26, 1963, at 04:17 UTC (5:17 am local time) in Skopje, Socialist Republic of Macedonia (present-day North Macedonia), then part of SFR Yugoslavia.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The tremor lasted for 20 seconds and was felt mostly along the Vardar River Valley.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] There were also smaller aftershocks until 5:43.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Following the earthquake, Josip Broz Tito, president of SFR Yugoslavia, sent a message of condolences to the Socialist Republic of Macedonia before visiting the city personally later on.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Within a few days after the earthquake took place, 35 nations requested that the United Nations General Assembly place relief for Skopje on their list of agendas.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The effort led to the implementation of a major urban and architectural reconstruction plan urban master-plan of Skopje 1963.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Relief, in the form of money, medical, engineering and building teams and supplies was offered from 78 countries throughout the world.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Kennedy ordered the Department of Defense and the Agency for International Development (USAID) to take actions for disaster assistance in Skopje by sending personnel, prefabricated houses, tent cities and other forms of relief.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Substantial relief also arrived from the Soviet Union.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Its leader, Nikita Khrushchev, visited Skopje personally.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] As the SFR Yugoslavia was a member of the Non-Aligned Movement during the Cold War, the American and Soviet troops stationed in Skopje could freely shake hands for the first time since their encounter on Elbe in 1945.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The first foreign journalist who arrived in Skopje to report on the earthquake was David Binder of *The New York Times*.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] As he watched Skopje from the plane, he commented that the city looked like it was bombed.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Dexion belongs to the Skopje's Municipality of Gjorče Petrov.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] At the same time, the UK Government made a gift of 44 x 24 feet wide Nissen huts which the Yugoslav authorities used as six schools to be used in satellite suburbs until permanent schools could be established.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The construction of these huts was under the supervision of a small detachment of nine Royal Engineers led by Lt Charles Brodley RE.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Later, "War on Want" purchased sufficient huts to provide accommodation for 2,000 workmen engaged in the reconstruction of the city and the Engineer detachment was increased to 49 under the command of Captain SL Rooth RE.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] In 1965, the Japanese architect Kenzo Tange was asked by the United Nations to enter a limited competition for the redevelopment of Skopje, after which Tange won 60% of the prize while the Yugoslav team won the remaining 40%.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] However, Tange's plan for Skopje (one of his major works) remains partly implemented, specifically concerning the New Skopje Railway Station and the so-called City Wall.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] As the city gradually began to recover, the need for revival of cultural life arose.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The artist Pablo Picasso donated his painting Head of a Woman (1963), which was exhibited in the new post-earthquake Contemporary Art Museum of Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The museum building was a donation from Poland and was designed by several Polish architects.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The concert hall "Univerzalna sala" was built with donations from around 35 countries and its prefabricated building was made in neighbouring Bulgaria.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Several streets and objects in Skopje were named in honor of the countries which helped in their construction and/or donated housing.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] For example, the government of Romania donated the polyclinic medical center, which was named after its capital, Bucharest.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] In Karposh Municipality, there are Soviet-donated apartment buildings called in Macedonian: „руски згради“ (*ruski zgradi*, meaning "Russian buildings") and Swedish and Finnish prefabs called „шведски / фински бараки“ (*švedski* / *finski baraki*).
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] One example is Skopje's Mexico Street (улица Мексичка, ulica Meksička).
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] It was officially named in honor of Mexico and a memorial plaque from the Mexican president Adolfo López Mateos was unveiled at the location.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] In 2012, the street's well-known resident, the rock musician Vlatko Stefanovski and his brother, the playwright Goran Stefanovski protested against the mayor's decision to rename several city streets, including Mexico Street.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The Stefanovski brothers reminded people that the street they grew up on and where the Macedonian rock group Leb i sol was formed was built with donations from Mexico and argued that this act of solidarity must never be forgotten.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The old name *Meksička* was brought back in February 2021 by the Skopje City Council.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] Being rebuilt from ruins thanks to the relief from all around the world, Skopje is often referred to as "The City of International Solidarity", which is its motto.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] One year after the 1963 Skopje earthquake, the first Yugoslavian Code for Construction in Seismic Regions (temporary code 1964), was prepared by a committee consisting of international and national experts.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] The Skopje earthquake is referenced in many works of art including literature, music, theatre and films.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] An example is the Macedonian feature film *Memento*, directed by Dimitrie Osmanli in 1967.
[src:north-macedonia/1963-skopje-earthquake] An example from the field of literature is the poem *Skoplje 1963* by the Austrian poet Christine Busta.
[src:north-macedonia/1972-danish-european-communities-membership-referendum] A referendum on joining the European Economic Community was held in Denmark on 2 October 1972.
[src:north-macedonia/1972-danish-european-communities-membership-referendum] The result was 63% in favour with a turnout of 90%.
[src:north-macedonia/1972-danish-european-communities-membership-referendum] The law that Denmark should be member of the EEC was passed on 11 October 1972, and Denmark became a member on 1 January 1973.
[src:north-macedonia/1972-danish-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to Article 20, section 2 of the Danish constitution, any law that makes limitations to the sovereignty of the Danish state (as membership of the EEC would) must be passed in the Danish parliament with 5/6 of the parliament's members voting for the law.
[src:north-macedonia/1972-danish-european-communities-membership-referendum] If a majority of members vote for the law, but not by 5/6 majority, and the government wishes to uphold the suggested law, the law can still be passed in a public referendum, as was the case in the 1972 referendum.
[src:north-macedonia/1972-danish-european-communities-membership-referendum] According to a 2022 study, municipalities that experienced more German-inflicted violence during the German occupation of Denmark in WWII were more likely to vote against joining the EEC.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The **1973 enlargement of the European Communities** was the first enlargement of the European Communities (EC), now the European Union (EU).
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Denmark, Ireland and the United Kingdom (UK) acceded to the EC on 1 January 1973.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Gibraltar and Greenland also joined the EC as part of the United Kingdom and Denmark respectively, but the Danish Faroe Islands, the other British Overseas Territories and the Crown dependencies of the United Kingdom did not join the EC.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Ireland and Denmark both held referendums in 1972 in May and October respectively, and the United Kingdom held a referendum in 1975, on membership of the EC, all which approved membership of the EC.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Norway planned to accede, but this was rejected in a referendum held in September 1972.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In 1992 Norway again applied to join, but voters again rejected the proposal in a 1994 referendum.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Greenland later withdrew from the EC on 1 January 1985 after a referendum in 1982.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] This was followed by the United Kingdom holding a referendum in 2016 on membership which resulted in the United Kingdom voting to leave the EU.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The United Kingdom was still recovering from the economic cost of the Second World War.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Ireland, while an independent state, was economically dependent on the UK, which accounted for nearly 75% of Ireland's exports, as codified in the Anglo-Irish Free trade agreement of 1966.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In 1960 the European Free Trade Association (EFTA) was established and was formed by Austria, Denmark, Norway, Portugal, Sweden, Switzerland and the United Kingdom.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] These countries were often referred to as the Outer Seven, as opposed to the Inner Six of the founding members of the European Community (EC).
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The EFTA was founded by a convention known as the Stockholm Convention in 1960, with the aim of liberalisation of trade in goods amongst its member states.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] On 31 July 1961 the United Kingdom, Ireland and Denmark applied to join the EC.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In 1963, after negotiations, France vetoed the United Kingdom's application because of the aversion of Charles de Gaulle to the UK, which he considered a "trojan horse" for the United States.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] De Gaulle resigned the French presidency in 1969.
[src:north-macedonia/1973-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In the 1970s, the EFTA states concluded free trade agreements with the EC.
[src:north-macedonia/1981-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The **1981 enlargement of the European Communities** was the second enlargement of what is now the European Union, then the European Communities (EC).
[src:north-macedonia/1981-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Greece acceded to the EEC on 1 January 1981.
[src:north-macedonia/1981-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] It is considered a part of the Mediterranean enlargement.
[src:north-macedonia/1981-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The application for accession was made on 12 July 1975, one year after the restoration of democracy in Greece.
[src:north-macedonia/1981-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In July 1976 negotiations began which ended in May 1979 with the signing of the Treaty of Accession.
[src:north-macedonia/1981-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Greece did not have a Referendum related to European Union accession.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Spain and Portugal acceded to the European Communities, now the European Union, in 1986.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] This was the third enlargement of the Communities, following on from the 1973 and 1981 enlargements.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Their accessions are considered to be a part of the broader Mediterranean enlargement of the European Union.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Spain and Portugal did not have a Referendum related to European Union accession.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Both countries had been under dictatorships until just over a decade prior to the accession, with Spain under the military dictatorship of Francisco Franco, and Portugal under the corporatist dictatorship of the *Estado Novo*.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] This had meant that, whilst both countries had previously had relationships with the Communities in some form or another, they were ineligible to become members.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The mid-1970s brought the death of Franco in Spain, and the Carnation Revolution in Portugal, which rapidly pushed both countries towards democracy.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Membership talks began with both countries a few years later.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Spain and Portugal acceded to the Communities on 1 January 1986.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The accession took place without any official ceremony other than the raising of the Spanish and Portuguese flags in Brussels, after a period of more than six years of negotiations between the Communities and the two countries.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Some scholars at the time predicted that increased competition from Europe would lead to economic problems for Spain and Portugal; however, in the years since, both countries' economies have benefited overall from the accession.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Spain first applied for association with the European Economic Community (EEC), the general economic arm of the three European Communities, on 10 February 1962.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] However, the application caused some controversy; a number of members of the European Parliament questioned whether the application was acceptable, given Spain's dictatorship.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] With the question of association still unresolved by 1964, the head of the Spanish mission to the EEC sent another letter on 14 February renewing the request for association status.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Talks were subsequently scheduled to begin in the autumn of that year.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Eventually, in 1967, the Council of the EEC approved a mandate for the commission to negotiate with Spain, and a trade agreement was signed in June 1970.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Discussions remained in the 1970s about what the future relationship between the EEC and Spain might look like, after the formation of an EEC–Spain joint committee.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Following the death of Spanish dictator Francisco Franco, who had ruled over the country for 36 years, and the beginnings of the Spanish transition to democracy, rumours had been circulating for some time in 1977 about the possibility of a Spanish request for membership of the EEC.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] On 26 July, the new democratic government of Spain led by Adolfo Suárez wrote three letters to the President of the Council of Ministers of the European Communities, Henri Simonet, each requesting the admission of Spain to each different European Community.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] These letters were hand-delivered by the Foreign Minister of Spain, Marcelino Oreja, to the President of the European Commission, Roy Jenkins, in Brussels on 28 July 1977.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] At the time, significant concerns were raised with regards to whether or not Spain would be accepted into the EEC.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Spanish press talked of a potential veto from France and Italy against its accession, on the basis of the potential threat it would pose to their agricultural sectors.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] However, more than a year after the application was made, after extensive consultation and negotiation with existing Member States, the European Commission published in November 1978 an official opinion on Spain's application for membership.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The opinion recommended that membership negotiations begin, but noted that the process to becoming a member of the EEC was likely to be a slow one, citing both financial and bureaucratic barriers.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] On 5 February 1979, negotiations were opened between Spain and the European Council – the committee of leaders of the Member States of the European Communities.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Roy Jenkins declared during a speech at the opening of the negotiations that "Spain is a part of Europe, and Europe is incomplete without Spain".
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] An attempted coup d'état in Spain in February 1981, in which elements of the Spanish Civil Guard attempted to remove the democratically elected government from office, represented a significant point of international attention during the membership negotiations.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The EEC was no exception to this, expressing its concern about the unfolding events.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The attempt was unsuccessful, and following its failure, the European Council met on 23–24 March 1981.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] It subsequently released a statement expressing its "great satisfaction at the reaction of the King, the government, and the Spanish people, faced by recent attacks against the democratic system of their country".
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In spite of this, the speed of the negotiations was not significantly increased by the events.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] A year later, the Spanish Socialist Workers' Party were elected into government following the 1982 Spanish general election, making González the Prime Minister.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Prior to the election, Spanish negotiations with the Communities had reportedly stalled; this was not only due to the coup attempt, but also thanks to opposition from the French government over concerns related to the Common Agricultural Policy leading to greater competition from Spain.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] González once again put emphasis on the EEC during his election campaign, and at the same time downplayed the issue of Spanish membership of NATO, which had been a controversial issue within the debate about opening Spain up to the world for a number of years.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Concerns were also raised over the potential impact of Spain's accession in particular on the operation of the Common Fisheries Policy.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The Spanish fishing fleet was larger than the entire fleet of the existing Community members put together, which had presented an issue in a similar manner during the negotiation of an interim agreement on fishing between Spain and the Community.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] It was evident during the Spanish negotiations for admission that Spain had become more responsive to the fishing sector, as a consequence of the high propensity of illegal fishing leading to fishermen "mobilising as a socio-occupational group".
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The Spanish Act of Accession eventually devoted fifty of its pages to fisheries-related matters, around 10% of the entire treaty.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Beginning to tire of the long negotiations by December 1983, the French government requested a deadline be imposed on the accession talks, proposing 30 September 1984 as the date.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The French government continued applying pressure in favour of this deadline into 1984, and it was agreed to by the Member States at the March 1984 Brussels Summit of the European Council.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] However, the agreed deadline was not met, with questions over fishing, agriculture and steel still remaining by the end of September, and more negotiations scheduled beyond the deadline.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] At the end of October 1984, a commitment was made that Spain and Portugal would join the Communities on 1 January 1986, although there remained "difficulties" still in a number of areas of the negotiations.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] This commitment was confirmed by a vote at the European Council summit on 3 December 1984, so long as "final negotiations [were] successful".
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In July 1959, just over a year after the EEC was established, the government of Portugal began the process of establishing a diplomatic mission to it, and to Euratom the same month.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] However, Portugal considered its "multi-continental structure" (in reference to its many overseas colonies) to be incompatible with EEC membership; even had it wished to join, its contemporary dictatorship would have made an accession difficult to impossible.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In spite of these factors, Portugal was a founding member of the European Free Trade Association (EFTA), which was initially aimed to compete with the EEC as a European common economic zone.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] EFTA, constituting something closer to a pure free trade zone than the EEC, was a more palatable prospect at the time for Portugal than taking on the full rules and regulations of the EEC.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] A Portuguese government report completed at the start of 1962 acknowledged that seeking entry as a member of the EEC would have been unlikely to end in success, and suggested that an application for associate status might have been a better option.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] A few months later, in April 1962, the Portuguese Ambassador to Brussels was instructed to open negotiations with the EEC to move towards this goal, in spite of potential hostilities due to "disapproval of the basic principles" of contemporary Portuguese government policy.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] However, the Portuguese government did not clarify what type of negotiations were being asked for, or what the future relationship they envisaged looked like.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The 1962 negotiations were later postponed indefinitely.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Portugal once again looked to open negotiations with the EEC in 1969.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] These negotiations were more fruitful, and eventually culminated in a trade agreement between the EEC and Portugal, albeit one that came at the same time as the EEC were negotiating free trade agreements with all Member States of EFTA.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Diplomatic efforts towards Portuguese membership of the EEC were restarted in the early 1970s, still during the time of the *Estado Novo* dictatorship, but with Marcelo Caetano having assumed the office of prime minister after Salazar's death.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Exploratory talks began in confidence on 7 January 1971, with Caetano's attitude to Portuguese-EEC relations being described as "pragmatic", seeing that Europe would continue to be incredibly important for the country as their main trading partner.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] On 19 December 1972, the EEC and the Portuguese government concluded an agreement significantly reducing tariffs on imports in trade between the two.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] This was the last move towards Europe on the part of Portugal before the fall of the *Estado Novo* regime.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Following the Carnation Revolution of 1974 and the first democratic elections in 1975, the new Portuguese government started to take greater steps towards European integration.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In June 1976, the exchange rate for units of account to US dollars meant the amount loaned at the time, UA 70 million, was worth $79.1 million, equivalent to $338,000,000 in 2024.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The first democratically elected government of Portugal spoke of its programme as one that "intends that Portugal be present in the common effort of democratic European countries in the political, economic, social and cultural transformation of the old continent".
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] These efforts bore their first fruits in September 1976, with the entrance of Portugal into the Council of Europe.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In 1977, just before Portugal made its formal application to join the Communities, Mário Soares, the prime minister of Portugal, and his foreign minister both went on a tour of European capitals, attempting to gather preliminary support for his country's accession.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Shortly afterwards, on 28 March, Portugal made their formal application to join the European Communities, with a series of three letters written by Soares to David Owen, the President of the council.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The Portuguese government at the time claimed that the application was not "the decision of a government" but rather "the decision of a people".
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Just over a year after the application was made, on 19 May 1978, the Commission issued a positive opinion on the Portuguese application for membership, following which membership negotiations were opened.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Although the opinion recommended that the Portuguese application be considered, it also highlighted significant dangers inherent to a Portuguese accession in the country's state at the time, noting that "profound social and economic reforms" would be required before admission could be successful.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Furthermore, at the end of 1979, after the government collapsed several times, Parliament was dissolved and fresh elections were called, leading to the election of a new prime minister, Francisco de Sá Carneiro.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] However, after having been in office for only a year, Carneiro died in the 1980 Camarate air crash.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] He was replaced as prime minister by Francisco Pinto Balsemão, whose government highlighted in their program concerns over "negative economic and social consequences" resulting from Community regulations that "suppose a different stage of structural evolution" in a Member State.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] During Balsemão's government, a new Transitional Protocol was agreed between the EEC and Portugal, adjusting some of the tariffs applicable to trade between the two, with "a view to the accession of the Portuguese Republic to the Communities".
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In 1983, amid a storm of resignations, Balsemão's government too collapsed, and the 1983 Portuguese legislative election was called.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The elections led to the return of the Socialist Party, and consequently the return of Mário Soares as prime minister.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] However, with insufficient support in the Portuguese Assembly, Soares was forced to form a coalition with Carneiro's party, the Social Democratic Party.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The new coalition's program stated that "accession to the EEC in good time and under the right conditions [...] is the top priority of Portuguese economic and foreign policy".
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In debates in the Portuguese Assembly, the Socialist Party, the Social Democratic Party and the Independent Social Democratic Association all expressed their agreement with the accession arrangements.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The Communist-led union Intersindical stood with the PCP, who still exist today, in opposing EEC membership, on the grounds of what they considered to be loss of economic control that it would cause.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] However, the Communist Party was the only Portuguese political party at the time consistently opposed to EEC membership, and they began to receive fewer and fewer votes starting in the mid-1980s, around the time of accession.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The status of the British Overseas Territory of Gibraltar was a significant sticking point in the negotiations for Spain's accession.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The Spanish Socialist Workers' Party were elected into government in 1982 on a manifesto including both EEC membership and a return of the territory to Spain.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Following the election, the Spanish government re-opened the border with Gibraltar to pedestrians on "humanitarian" grounds, which laid the foundation for further negotiations with the United Kingdom, although no other types of traffic were permitted through.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] These negotiations continued for some time, with one suggestion being that the territory could be turned into a NATO military base with shared sovereignty as a consequence.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The negotiations surrounding the status of Gibraltar were described at the time by Fernando Morán, the Spanish foreign minister, as "the most decisive and delicate moment" of Spain's accession negotiations.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The government of the United Kingdom at the time declared themselves publicly to be in favour of Portugal and Spain joining the Communities, with the Minister of State for the Foreign and Commonwealth Office saying that the country had been a "staunch supporter of the accession".
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Thatcher's government's insistence on a complete re-opening of the border prior to EEC entry "angered" the Spanish government of the time; however, they also said that they would be prepared to allow vehicular and other crossings, rather than just those on foot.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] After even further protracted negotiations, the border was fully reopened on 5 February 1985.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] From 1982 onwards, Greece had been trying to secure approval by the European Council for the Integrated Mediterranean Programmes (IMPs), a series of financial aid measures for disadvantaged regions of the Communities.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Having had little success, and with the idea still under "consideration" by the Council several years later, Greece threatened to veto the accessions of Spain and Portugal.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The veto was based on Greece's claims that its economy would not be able to cope with more economically weak Member States joining, without receiving agricultural subsidies for its poorest regions that had not yet been approved.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In late 1984, Andreas Papandreou, the prime minister of Greece, formally confirmed that the only blocker for Greek approval of the accessions was the availability of financial subsidy through the IMPs.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Negotiations continued on into 1985, and on 29 May, the Italian Minister for Foreign Affairs Giulio Andreotti, in conjunction with Spain's Fernando Morán and the Portuguese Finance Minister Ernâni Lopes, announced that an agreement had been reached.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Some parts of the IMPs would be implemented, thereby increasing EEC funding to Greece; consequentially, Greece dropped its reservations, and Portugal and Spain would enter the "Europe of Twelve" on 1 January 1986.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In total, Greece received US$2,000,000,000 in additional aid as a consequence of the negotiations, equivalent to $6,000,000,000 in 2025.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Membership of the Communities is widely seen as having assisted the transitions to democracy of Spain and Portugal; however, there is some debate as to what extent Community membership is responsible for this.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The prerequisite that a state should be a democracy before joining the Communities has been described as a motivating factor for democratisation, and such a requirement has been suggested for agreements such as the North American Free Trade Agreement as a result.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Eurobarometer surveys between 1985 and 1997 found a significant majority of Portuguese citizens felt that EU membership had benefited their country; this peaked at 82% of the population in 1991, before falling to a low of 67% in 1997.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Special arrangements agreed for Spain and Portugal as new EEC members meant that, whilst in principle they were subject to the *acquis communautaire* of the Common Fisheries Policy, they were not fully integrated into it for many years.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] However, other scholars have argued that the eventual benefit from the *acquis* has outweighed this, and pointed out that Spain has come to ardently insist on new EU members taking up the entire *acquis*.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Shortly after formally joining in 1986, both Spain and Portugal agreed to proposed changes to the Treaty of Rome which limited individual countries' abilities to veto proposed legislation affecting tariffs and trade, and committed to a common foreign policy for Community Member States.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] They also expressed themselves to be in favour of a doubling of the research budget of the EEC over a period of 5 years.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The accession of Portugal to the European Communities also had an impact on the decolonisation of Portuguese colonies in Africa and on Europe-Africa relations consequently.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] The accession led to significant benefits for both in terms of economic stability and strength, and the average per-capita income of Portuguese and Spanish citizens grew significantly, reaching 74% and 83% respectively of the EU average by 2003.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] Structural funds offered by European Community membership were of particular importance in easing pressure on the countries' economies, especially following the Single European Act reforms that doubled the amount of structural funds available between 1988 and 1993.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] In Portugal, these funds were invested primarily in road infrastructure, public buildings and urban renewal, indirectly creating many new jobs in the construction industry, which led to a significant (if small in absolute terms) increase in "unskilled or low-skilled" migration to the country.
[src:north-macedonia/1986-enlargement-of-the-european-communities] "Restrictive administrative practices" in Spain, however, are noted as having "penalised" products from abroad, placing a preference on locally produced ones.
[src:north-macedonia/mk] Registration is possible directly at the second level without any restrictions.
[src:north-macedonia/mk] Registrations under a number of second level domains are also possible, however those use of those domains are restricted to certain entities.
[src:north-macedonia/mk] The Internationalized Cyrillic country code top-level domain .мкд was officially approved and registered on March 20, 2014.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The region's history begins with the kingdom of Paeonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In the late sixth century BC, the area was subjugated by the Persian Achaemenid Empire, then incorporated into the Kingdom of Macedonia in the fourth century BC.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Roman Republic conquered the region in the second century BC and made it part of its larger province of Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The area remained part of the Byzantine Empire, but was often raided and settled by Slavic tribes beginning in the sixth century CE.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Following centuries of contention between the Bulgarian, Byzantine, and Serbian Empires, it was part of the Ottoman Empire from the mid-14th until the early 20th century, when, following the Balkan Wars of 1912 and 1913, the modern territory of North Macedonia came under Serbian rule.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] During the First World War, the territory was ruled by Bulgaria.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] After the end of the war, it returned to Serbian rule as part of the newly formed Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] During the Second World War, it was again ruled by Bulgaria; and in 1945 it was established as a constituent state of communist Yugoslavia, which it remained until its peaceful secession in 1991.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The country became a member of the United Nations (UN) in 1993.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia is a member of NATO, the Council of Europe, the World Bank, OSCE, CEFTA, BSEC and the WTO.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Since 2005, it has also been a candidate for joining the European Union.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia is an upper-middle-income country by the World Bank's definitions and has undergone considerable economic reform since its independence in developing an open economy.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It is a developing country, ranking 68th on the Human Development Index, with low income inequality.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The country provides social security, a universal health care system as well as free primary and secondary education to its citizens.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The state's name derives from the Greek word Μακεδονία (*Makedonía*), a kingdom (later, region) named after the ancient Macedonians.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Their name, Μακεδόνες (*Makedónes*), ultimately derives from the ancient Greek adjective μακεδνός (*makednós*), meaning 'tall' or 'taper', which shares the same root as the adjective μακρός (*makrós*, 'long, tall, high') in ancient Greek.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The name is believed to have originally meant either 'highlanders' or 'the tall ones', possibly descriptive of the people.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Beekes, both terms are of pre-Greek substrate origin and cannot be explained in terms of Indo-European morphology.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] According to linguist Filip De Decker, Beekes's arguments are insufficiently supported.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Apart from the Byzantine theme of Macedonia, the name "Macedonia" was largely forgotten as a geographical denomination through the Byzantine and Ottoman eras but was revived by Bulgarian and Greek nationalist movements from the early 19th century onwards.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It was revived only in middle of the century, with the rise of nationalism in the Ottoman Empire.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In the early 20th century the region was already a national cause, contested among Bulgarian, Greek, and Serbian nationalists.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] During the interwar period the use of the name "Macedonia" was prohibited in the Kingdom of Yugoslavia, due to the implemented policy of Serbianisation of the local Slavic-speakers.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The name "Macedonia" was adopted officially for the first time at the end of the Second World War by the new Socialist Republic of Macedonia, which became one of the six constituent countries of the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] After the breakup of Yugoslavia, this federal entity declared independence and proclaimed as its official name the "Republic of Macedonia" in 1991.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Prespa agreement of June 2018 saw the country change its name to the "Republic of North Macedonia" eight months later.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] A non-binding national referendum on the matter passed with 90% approval but did not reach the required 50% turnout amidst a boycott, leaving the final decision with parliament to ratify the result.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Parliament approved of the name change on 19 October, reaching the required two-thirds majority needed to enact constitutional changes.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The vote to amend the constitution and change the name of the country passed on 11 January 2019 in favour of the amendment.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The amendment entered into force on 12 February, following the ratification of the Prespa agreement and the Protocol on the Accession of North Macedonia to NATO by the Greek Parliament.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Many of the country's citizens and local media outlets unofficially refer to the country as "Macedonia".
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia geographically roughly corresponds to the ancient kingdom of Paeonia, which was located immediately north of the ancient kingdom of Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In early times, the chief town and seat of the Paeonian kings was Bylazora (in modern Sveti Nikole municipality in North Macedonia) on the Vardar; later, the seat of the kings was moved to Stobi (near modern Gradsko).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Paeonia was inhabited by the Paeonians, whilst the northwest was inhabited by the Illyrian Dardani and southwest by the Enchelae (also an Illyrian tribe), as well as Pelagones and Lyncestae of Upper Macedonia (generally regarded as Molossian tribes of the northwestern Greek group).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In the late 6th century BC, the Achaemenid Persians under Darius the Great conquered Paeonia, incorporating the area within their vast territories.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Following their defeat in the Second Persian invasion of Greece in 479 BC, the Persians eventually withdrew from their European territories.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Philip II of Macedon absorbed the regions of Lynkestis, Pelagonia and the southern part of Paeonia (Deuriopus) into the kingdom of Macedon in 356 BC.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] After the death of Agis, the kingdom of Paeonia then led by Lycceius, became vassal to Philip II in 356 BC.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] A Paeonian cavalry contingent, led by Ariston, possibly brother of King Patraus and father of the later king Audoleon, was attached to Alexander the Great's army.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Alexander wished to bestow the hand of his sister Cynane upon Langarus, king of the Agrianians, who had shown himself loyal to Philip II.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Scupi and the surrounding area remained part of Dardania.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 310 BC, Celtic armies attacked the area, but were defeated by Cassander.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 279, the Gauls defeated Ptolemy Ceraunus and got as far as Delphi and it is certain that Paeonia was overrun and held for a time by their chieftain Brennus, but in the wake of the Celtic invasion, Leon reestablished the Paeonian kingdom.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 230 BC the Dardani under Longarus captured Bylazora.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 227 BC, Antigonus Doson reconquered the southern part of Paeonia and founded the city of Antigoneia, and ten years after Philip V of Macedon captured Bylazora; after this Perseis and Astraion were founded.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Romans established the province of Macedonia in 146 BC.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] This comprised most of the territory of the modern country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Roman expansion brought the Scupi area under Roman rule in the time of Domitian (81–96 AD), and it fell within the Province of Moesia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Whilst Greek remained the dominant language in the eastern part of the Roman empire, especially south of the Jireček Line, Latin spread to Macedonia to some extent.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Slavic tribes settled in the Balkan region including North Macedonia by the late 6th century AD.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Slavs settled on places of earlier settlements and probably merged later with the local populations to form mixed Byzantine-Slavic communities.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] 680 a Bulgar ruler called Kuber led a group of largely Christians called Sermesianoi, who were his subjects, and they settled in the region of Pelagonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] They may have consisted of Bulgars, Byzantines, Slavs and even Germanic tribes.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] There is no more information of Kuber's life.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Presian's reign apparently coincides with the extension of Bulgarian control over the Slavic tribes in and around Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Slavic tribes that settled in the region of Macedonia converted to Christianity around the 9th century during the reign of Tsar Boris I of Bulgaria.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Ohrid Literary School became one of the two major cultural centres of the First Bulgarian Empire, along with the Preslav Literary School.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Established in Ohrid in 886 by Saint Clement of Ohrid on the order of Boris I, the Ohrid Literary School was involved in the spreading of the Cyrillic script.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] After Sviatoslav's invasion of Bulgaria, the Byzantines took control of eastern Bulgaria.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] He moved the capital to Skopje and then to Ohrid, which had been the cultural and military centre of southwestern Bulgaria since Boris I's rule.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Samuil re-established Bulgarian power, but after several decades of conflicts, in 1014, the Byzantine Emperor Basil II defeated his armies, and within four years the Byzantines restored control over the Balkans (modern-day North Macedonia was included into a new province, called Bulgaria).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The rank of the autocephalous Bulgarian Patriarchate was lowered due to its subjugation to Constantinople and it was transformed into the Archbishopric of Ohrid.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] By the late 12th century, Byzantine decline saw the region contested by various political entities, including a brief Norman occupation in the 1080s.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In the early 13th century, a revived Bulgarian Empire gained control of the region.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Plagued by political difficulties, the empire did not last, and the region came once again under Byzantine control in the early 14th century.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In the 14th century, it became part of the Serbian Empire.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Skopje became the capital of Tsar Stefan Dušan's empire.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Following Dušan's death, a weak successor appeared, and power struggles between nobles divided the Balkans once again.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] These events coincided with the entry of the Ottoman Turks into Europe.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Kingdom of Prilep was one of the short-lived states that emerged from the collapse of the Serbian Empire in the 14th century and was seized by the Ottomans at the end of the same century.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Gradually, all of the central Balkans were conquered by the Ottoman Empire and remained under its domination for five centuries as part of the province or Eyalet of Rumelia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The name *Rumelia* (Turkish: *Rumeli*) means "Land of the Romans" in Turkish, referring to the lands conquered by the Ottoman Turks from the Byzantine Empire.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Over the centuries, Rumelia Eyalet was reduced in size through administrative reforms, until by the 19th century it consisted of a region of central Albania and western North Macedonia with its capital at Manastir or present-day Bitola.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Rumelia Eyalet was abolished in 1867 and that territory of Macedonia subsequently became part of vilayets of Manastir, Kosova and Selanik until the end of Ottoman rule in 1912.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] With the beginning of the Bulgarian National Revival in the 19th century, many of the reformers were from this region, including the Miladinov brothers, Rajko Žinzifov, Joakim Krčovski, Kiril Pejčinoviḱ and others.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The bishoprics of Skopje, Debar, Bitola, Ohrid, Veles, and Strumica voted to join the Bulgarian Exarchate after it was established in 1870.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 1905 it was renamed the Internal Macedonian-Adrianople Revolutionary Organization (IMARO), and after World War I the organisation separated into the Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization (IMRO) and the Internal Thracian Revolutionary Organisation (ITRO).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In the early years of the organisation, membership eligibility was exclusive to Bulgarians, but later it was extended to all inhabitants of European Turkey regardless of ethnicity or religion.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The majority of its members were Macedonian Bulgarians.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 1903, IMRO organised the Ilinden–Preobrazhenie Uprising against the Ottomans, which after some initial successes, including the forming of the Kruševo Republic, was crushed with much loss of life.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The uprising and the forming of the Kruševo Republic are considered the cornerstone and precursors to the eventual establishment of the Macedonian state.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The leaders of the Ilinden uprising are celebrated as national heroes in North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The names of IMRO revolutionaries like Gotse Delchev, Pitu Guli, Dame Gruev and Yane Sandanski were included into the lyrics of the national anthem of the state of North Macedonia "Denes nad Makedonija" ("Today over Macedonia").
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The major national holiday of North Macedonia, the Republic Day, is celebrated on 2 August, Ilinden (St.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Elijah day), the day of the Ilinden uprising.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Following the two Balkan Wars of 1912 and 1913 and the dissolution of the Ottoman Empire, most of its European-held territories were divided between Greece, Bulgaria and Serbia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Most of the territory that was to become North Macedonia was annexed by Serbia conforming to the treaty of peace concluded at Bucharest.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] However, Strumica region was passed to Bulgaria.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Following the partition, an anti-Bulgarian campaign was carried out in the areas under Serbian and Greek control.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] As many as 641 Bulgarian schools and 761 churches were closed by the Serbs, while Exarchist clergy and teachers were expelled.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The use of all Macedonian dialects and standard Bulgarian were proscribed.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] IMRO, together with local Albanians, organised the Ohrid–Debar uprising against the Serbian rule.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Within a few days the rebels captured the towns of Gostivar, Struga and Ohrid, expelling the Serbian troops.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] According to the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace report, a Serbian army of 100,000 regulars suppressed the uprising.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Many were killed and tens of thousands of refugees fled to Bulgaria and Albania.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] During the First World War, most of today's North Macedonia was part of the Bulgarian occupied zone of Serbia after the country was invaded by the Central Powers in the fall of 1915.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The region was known as the "Military Inspection Area of Macedonia" and was administered by a Bulgarian military commander.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] A policy of Bulgarisation of the region and its population was immediately initiated, during the period the IMRO arose from a clandestine organisation to serve as gendarmerie, taking control of the whole police structure, enforcing the Bulgarisation of the region.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] According to Robert Gerwarth, the Bulgarian denationalisation policy, including its paramilitary aspect, was almost identical in its intent and execution to the Serbian policy that preceded it.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Adult males were sent to labour camps or forced to join the Bulgarian Army, representatives of the Serbian intelligentsia were deported or executed.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] According to Paul Mojzes the aim of the Bulgarian government was to create pure Bulgarian territories by denationalising the non-Bulgarian Slavic population of Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] After the capitulation of Bulgaria and the end of the First World War, the area returned under Belgrade control as part of the newly formed Kingdom of Serbs, Croats and Slovenes and saw a reintroduction of anti-Bulgarian measures.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Bulgarian teachers and clergy were expelled, Bulgarian language signs and books removed, and all Bulgarian organisations dissolved.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Also after the Treaty of Neuilly-sur-Seine, the Strumica region was annexed to Serbian Macedonia in 1919.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Serbian government pursued a policy of forced Serbianisation in the region, which included systematic suppression of Bulgarian activists, altering family surnames, internal colonisation, exploiting workers, and intense propaganda.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] To aid the implementation of this policy, some 50,000 Serbian army and gendarmerie were stationed in present-day North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] By 1940 about 280 Serbian colonies (comprising 4,200 families) were established as part of the government's internal colonisation program (initial plans envisaged 50,000 families settling in present-day North Macedonia).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 1929, the Kingdom was officially renamed the Kingdom of Yugoslavia, and divided into provinces called *banovinas*.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] South Serbia, including all of present-day North Macedonia, became the Vardar Banovina of the Kingdom of Yugoslavia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Internal Macedonian Revolutionary Organization (IMRO) promoted the concept of an Independent Macedonia in the interwar period.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Its leaders—including Todor Alexandrov, Aleksandar Protogerov, and Ivan Mihailov—promoted independence of the Macedonian territory split between Serbia and Greece for the whole population, regardless of religion and ethnicity.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Bulgarian government of Alexander Malinov in 1918 offered to give Pirin Macedonia for that purpose after World War I, but the Great Powers did not adopt this idea because Serbia and Greece opposed it.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 1924, the Communist International (Comintern) suggested that all Balkan communist parties adopt a platform of a "United Macedonia" but the suggestion was rejected by the Bulgarian and Greek communists.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] IMRO followed by starting an insurgent war in Vardar Macedonia, together with Macedonian Youth Secret Revolutionary Organization, which also conducted guerrilla attacks against the Serbian administrative and army officials there.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 1923 in Stip, a paramilitary organisation called Association against Bulgarian Bandits was formed by Serbian chetniks, IMRO renegades and Macedonian Federative Organization (MFO) members to oppose IMRO and MMTRO.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] On 9 October 1934, IMRO member Vlado Chernozemski assassinated Alexander I of Yugoslavia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Macedonist ideas increased in Yugoslav Vardar Macedonia and among the left diaspora in Bulgaria during the interwar period.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In 1934, the Comintern issued a special resolution in which for the first time directions were provided for recognising the existence of a separate Macedonian nation and Macedonian language.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] During World War II, Yugoslavia was occupied by the Axis powers from 1941 to 1945.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Vardar Banovina was divided between Bulgaria and Italian-occupied Albania.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Bulgarian Action Committees were established to prepare the region for the new Bulgarian administration and army.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The committees were mostly formed by former members of IMRO and Macedonian Youth Secret Revolutionary Organization (MYSRO, but some IMRO (United) former members also participated.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] As leader of the Vardar Macedonian communists, Metodi Shatorov ("Sharlo") switched from the Yugoslav Communist Party to the Bulgarian Communist Party and refused to start military action against the Bulgarian Army.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Bulgarian authorities, under German pressure, were responsible for the round-up and deportation of over 7,000 Jews in Skopje and Bitola.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Harsh rule by the occupying forces encouraged many Vardar Macedonians to support the Communist Partisan resistance movement of Josip Broz Tito after 1943, and the National Liberation War ensued.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In Vardar Macedonia, after the Bulgarian coup d'état of 1944, the Bulgarian troops, surrounded by German forces, fought their way back to the old borders of Bulgaria.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Under the leadership of the new Bulgarian pro-Soviet government, four armies, 455,000 strong in total, were mobilised and reorganised.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Most of them re-entered occupied Yugoslavia in early October 1944 and moved from Sofia to Niš, Skopje and Pristina with the strategic task of blocking the German forces withdrawing from Greece.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Bulgarian army would reach the Alps in Austria, participating in the expulsion of the Germans to the west, through Yugoslavia and Hungary.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Compelled by the Soviet Union with a view towards the creation of a large South Slav Federation, in 1946 the new Communist government, led by Georgi Dimitrov, agreed to give Bulgarian Macedonia to a United Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] With the Bled agreement, in 1947 Bulgaria formally confirmed the envisioned unification of the Macedonian region, but postponed this act until after the formation of the future Federation.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It was the first time it accepted the existence of a separate Macedonian ethnicity and language.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] After the Tito–Stalin split the region of Pirin Macedonia remained part of Bulgaria and later the Bulgarian Communist Party revised its view of the existence of a separate Macedonian nation and language.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In December 1944, the Anti-fascist Assembly for the National Liberation of Macedonia (ASNOM) proclaimed the People's Republic of Macedonia as part of the People's Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] ASNOM remained an acting government until the end of the war.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Macedonian alphabet was codified by linguists of ASNOM, who based their alphabet on the phonetic alphabet of Vuk Stefanović Karadžić and the principles of Krste Petkov Misirkov.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] During the civil war in Greece (1946–1949), Macedonian communist insurgents supported the Greek communists.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Many refugees fled to the Socialist Republic of Macedonia from there.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The state removed "Socialist" from its name in 1991 when it peacefully seceded from Yugoslavia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The new republic became one of the six republics of the Yugoslav federation.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Following the federation's renaming as the Socialist Federal Republic of Yugoslavia in 1963, the People's Republic of Macedonia was likewise renamed the Socialist Republic of Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia officially celebrates 8 September 1991 as Independence day (Macedonian: Ден на независноста, *Den na nezavisnosta*), with regard to the referendum endorsing independence from Yugoslavia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The anniversary of the start of the Ilinden Uprising (St.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Elijah's Day) on 2 August is also widely celebrated on an official level as the Day of the Republic.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Robert Badinter, as the head of the Arbitration Commission of the Peace Conference on Yugoslavia, recommended EC recognition in January 1992.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] On 15 January 1992, Bulgaria was the first country to recognise the independence of the republic.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Macedonia remained at peace through the Yugoslav Wars of the early 1990s.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] A few very minor changes to its border with Yugoslavia were agreed upon to resolve problems with the demarcation line between the two countries.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It was seriously destabilised by the Kosovo War in 1999, when an estimated 360,000 ethnic Albanian refugees from Kosovo took refuge in the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] They departed shortly after the war, and Albanian nationalists on both sides of the border took up arms soon after in pursuit of autonomy or independence for the Albanian-populated areas of Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] A conflict took place between the government and ethnic Albanian insurgents, mostly in the north and west of the country, between February and August 2001.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The war ended with the intervention of a NATO ceasefire monitoring force.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Under the terms of the Ohrid Agreement, the government agreed to devolve greater political power and cultural recognition to the Albanian minority.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Albanian side agreed to abandon separatist demands and to recognise all Macedonian institutions fully.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In addition, according to this accord, the NLA were to disarm and hand over their weapons to a NATO force.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] However the Macedonian security forces had two more armed confrontations with Albanian militant groups, in 2007 and 2015 respectively.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Inter-ethnic tensions flared in Macedonia in 2012, with incidents of violence between ethnic Albanians and Macedonians.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In April 2017, about 200 protesters - reportedly mostly from the conservative VMRO-DPMNE party, stormed the Macedonian Parliament in response to the election of Talat Xhaferi, an ethnic Albanian and former National Liberation Army commander during the 2001 conflict, as the Speaker of the Assembly.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Upon its coming to power in 2006, but especially since the country's non-invitation to NATO in 2008, the VMRO-DPMNE government pursued a policy of "Antiquisation" ("Antikvizatzija") as a way of putting pressure on Greece as well as for the purposes of domestic identity-building.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Statues of Alexander the Great and Philip of Macedon have been erected in several cities across the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Additionally, many pieces of public infrastructure, such as airports, highways, and stadiums were renamed after Alexander and Philip.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] These actions were seen as deliberate provocations in neighbouring Greece, exacerbating the dispute and further stalling the country's EU and NATO applications.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The policy has also attracted criticism domestically, as well as from EU diplomats, and, following the Prespa agreement, it has been partly reversed after 2016 by the new SDSM government of North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Moreover, per Prespa agreement both countries have acknowledged that their respective understanding of the terms "Macedonia" and "Macedonian" refers to a different historical context and cultural heritage.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In August 2017, what was then the Republic of Macedonia signed a friendship agreement with Bulgaria, aiming to end the "anti-Bulgarian ideology" in the country and to solve the historical issues between the two.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Under the Prespa agreement, signed with Greece on 17 June 2018, the country agreed to change its name to the Republic of North Macedonia and stop public use of the Vergina Sun.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It retained the demonym "Macedonian", but clarified this as distinct from the Greek Macedonian identity in northern Greece.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The agreement also included removal of irredentist material from textbooks and maps in both countries.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It replaced the bilateral Interim Accord of 1995.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The withdrawal of the Greek veto, along with the signing the friendship agreement with Bulgaria, resulted in the European Union on 27 June approving the start of accession talks, which were expected to take place in 2019, under the condition that the Prespa deal was implemented.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] On 5 July, the Prespa agreement was ratified by the Macedonian parliament with 69 MPs voting in favour of it.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] On 12 July, NATO invited Macedonia to start accession talks in a bid to become the alliance's 30th member.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] On 30 July, the parliament of Macedonia approved plans to hold a non-binding referendum on changing the country's name, which took place on 30 September.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Ninety-one percent of voters voted in favour with a 37% turnout, but the referendum was not carried because of a constitutional requirement for a 50% turnout.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] On 6 February 2019, the permanent representatives of NATO member states and Macedonian Foreign Affairs Minister Nikola Dimitrov, signed in Brussels the accession protocol of North Macedonia into NATO.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The protocol was then ratified on 8 February by the Greek parliament, thus completing all the preconditions for putting into force the Prespa agreement.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Subsequently, on 12 February the Macedonian government announced the formal activation of the constitutional amendments which effectively renamed the country as North Macedonia and informed accordingly the United Nations and its member states.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In March 2020, after the ratification process by all NATO members was completed, North Macedonia acceded to NATO, becoming the 30th member state.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In March 2020, the leaders of the European Union formally gave approval to North Macedonia to begin talks to join the EU.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] On 17 November 2020, Bulgaria refused to approve the European Union's negotiation framework for North Macedonia, effectively blocking the official start of accession talks with this country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The explanation from the Bulgarian side was: no implementation of the friendship treaty from 2017, state-supported hate speech, minority claims, and an "ongoing nation-building process" based on historical negationism of the Bulgarian identity, culture and legacy in the broader region of Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The veto received condemnation by intellectuals from both states and criticism from international observers.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Protests broke out in July 2022, organised by the opposition parties, over the French proposal for the accession of North Macedonia to the EU.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The accession talks for the accession of North Macedonia to the EU officially began in the same month, after the French proposal was passed by the Assembly of North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The 2023 European Commission Progress Report has cited the unfulfilled constitutional changes, as the primary reasons for the blocking of the further country's accession path.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The EU's intention regarding the country's accession seems unclear, excluding desire to maintain its geopolitical influence here, countering the Chinese and Russian impact in the Western Balkans.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] On 25 September 2024, the EU announced the separation of Albania from North Macedonia on the EU accession path, due to the disputes between North Macedonia and Bulgaria.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Following the decision, the EU opened negotiations on the first chapters with Albania separately on October 15, 2024.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia has a total area of 25,436 km2 (9,821 sq mi).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It lies between latitudes 40° and 43° N, and mostly between longitudes 20° and 23° E (a small area lies east of 23°).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia has some 748 km (465 mi) of boundaries, shared with Serbia (62 km or 39 mi) to the North, Kosovo (159 km or 99 mi) to the northwest, Bulgaria (148 km or 92 mi) to the east, Greece (228 km or 142 mi) to the south, and Albania (151 km or 94 mi) to the west.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It is a transit way for shipment of goods from Greece, through the Balkans, towards Eastern, Western and Central Europe and through Bulgaria to the east.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It is part of the larger region of Macedonia, which also includes Greek Macedonia and the Blagoevgrad Province in southwestern Bulgaria.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia is a landlocked country that is geographically clearly defined by a central valley formed by the Vardar river and framed along its borders by mountain ranges.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The terrain is mostly rugged, located between the Šar Mountains and Osogovo, which frame the valley of the Vardar river.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Three large lakes—Lake Ohrid, Lake Prespa and Dojran Lake—lie on the southern borders, bisected by the frontiers with Albania and Greece.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Ohrid is considered to be one of the oldest lakes and biotopes in the world.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The region is seismically active and has been the site of destructive earthquakes in the past, most recently in 1963 when Skopje was heavily damaged by a major earthquake, killing over 1,000.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia also has scenic mountains.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] They belong to two different mountain ranges: the first is the Šar Mountains that continues to the West Vardar/Pelagonia group of mountains (Baba Mountain, Nidže, Kožuf and Jakupica), also known as the Dinaric range.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The second range is the Osogovo–Belasica mountain chain, also known as the Rhodope range.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The mountains belonging to the Šar Mountains and the West Vardar/Pelagonia range are younger and higher than the older mountains of the Osogovo-Belasica mountain group.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Mount Korab of the Šar Mountains on the Albanian border, at 2,764 m (9,068 ft), is the tallest mountain in North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In North Macedonia there are 1,100 large sources of water.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The rivers flow into three different basins: the Aegean, the Adriatic and the Black Sea.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It covers 87% of the territory of North Macedonia, which is 22,075 square kilometres (8,523 sq mi).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Vardar, the largest river in this basin, drains 80% of the territory or 20,459 square kilometres (7,899 sq mi).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Its valley plays an important part in the economy and the communication system of the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Vardar Valley project is considered to be crucial for the strategic development of the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The river Black Drin forms the Adriatic basin, which covers an area of about 3,320 km2 (1,282 sq mi), i.e., 13% of the territory.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It receives water from Lakes Prespa and Ohrid.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The Black Sea basin is the smallest with only 37 km2 (14 sq mi).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] It covers the northern side of Mount Skopska Crna Gora.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] This is the source of the river Binačka Morava, which joins the Morava, and later, the Danube, which flows into the Black Sea.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia has around fifty ponds and three natural lakes, Lake Ohrid, Lake Prespa and Lake Dojran.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] In North Macedonia there are nine spa towns and resorts: Banište, Banja Bansko, Istibanja, Katlanovo, Kežovica, Kosovrasti, Banja Kočani, Kumanovski Banji and Negorci.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Four different seasons are found in the country with warm and dry summers and moderately cold and snowy winters.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The range of temperatures recorded throughout the year ranges from −20 °C (−4 °F) in winter, to 40 °C (104 °F) in summer.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Low winter temperatures are influenced by winds from the north while heat seasons during summer arise due to the subtropical pressure of the Aegean Sea and climate influences from the Middle East, with the latter causing dry periods.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] There are three main climatic zones in the country: mildly continental in the north, temperate Mediterranean in the south and mountainous in the zones with high altitude.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Along the valleys of the Vardar and Strumica rivers, in the regions of Gevgelija, Valandovo, Dojran, Strumica, and Radoviš, the climate is temperate Mediterranean.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The warmest regions are Demir Kapija and Gevgelija, where the temperature in July and August frequently exceeds 40 °C (104 °F).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Average annual precipitation varies from 1,700 mm (66.9 in) in the western mountainous area to 500 mm (19.7 in) in the eastern area.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] There is a low level of precipitation in the Vardar valley with 500 mm (19.7 in) of water per year.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The climate and irrigation diversity allow the cultivation of different plant types, including wheat, maize, potatoes, poppies, peanuts, and rice.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] There are thirty main and regular weather stations in the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The flora of North Macedonia is represented by around 210 families, 920 genera, and around 3,700 plant species.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The most abundant group are the flowering plants with around 3,200 species, followed by mosses (350 species) and ferns (42).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Phytogeographically, North Macedonia belongs to the Illyrian province of the Circumboreal Region within the Boreal Kingdom.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] North Macedonia had a 2019 Forest Landscape Integrity Index mean score of 7.42/10, ranking it 40th globally out of 172 countries.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The native forest fauna is abundant and includes bears, wild boars, wolves, foxes, squirrels, chamois and deer.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] The lynx is found, very rarely, in the mountains of western Macedonia, while deer can be found in the region of Demir Kapija.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p01] Forest birds include the blackcap, the grouse, the black grouse, the imperial eagle and the forest owl.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia is a parliamentary democracy with an executive government composed of a coalition of parties from the unicameral legislature (Собрание, *Sobranie*; *Assembly* in English) and an independent judicial branch with a constitutional court.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Assembly is made up of 120 seats and the members are elected every four years.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The role of the president is mostly ceremonial, with the real power resting in the hands of the prime minister.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The president is the commander-in-chief of the state armed forces and a president of the State Security Council.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The president is elected every five years and he or she can be elected twice at most.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Since 2019, local government functions are divided between 80 municipalities (општини, *opštini*; singular: општина, *opština*).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The capital, Skopje, is governed as a group of ten municipalities collectively referred to as the "City of Skopje".
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Municipalities in North Macedonia are units of local self-government.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Neighbouring municipalities may establish co-operative arrangements.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The country's main political divergence is between the largely ethnically based political parties representing the country's ethnic Macedonian majority and Albanian minority.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The issue of the power balance between the two communities led to a brief war in 2001, following which a power-sharing agreement was reached.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In August 2004, parliament passed legislation redrawing local boundaries and giving greater local autonomy to ethnic Albanians in areas where they predominate.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] After a troublesome pre-election campaign, North Macedonia saw a relatively calm and democratic change of government in the elections held on 5 July 2006.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The elections were marked by a decisive victory of the centre-right party VMRO-DPMNE led by Nikola Gruevski.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] A dialogue was later established between the Democratic Union for Integration and the ruling VMRO-DMPNE party as an effort to talk about the disputes between the two parties and to support European and NATO aspirations of the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] After the early parliamentary elections held in 2008, VMRO-DPMNE and Democratic Union for Integration formed a ruling coalition.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In April 2009, presidential and local elections in the country were carried out peacefully, which was crucial for Macedonian aspirations to join the EU.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The ruling conservative VMRO-DPMNE party won a victory in the local elections and the candidate supported by the party, Gjorgi Ivanov, was elected as the new president.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In June 2017, Zoran Zaev of the Social Democratic Party, became the new prime minister six months after early elections.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The new centre-left government ended 11 years of conservative VMRO-DPMNE rule led by former prime minister Nikola Gruevski.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] As of 4 January 2020, the acting prime minister of North Macedonia was Oliver Spasovski and the president of the Parliament was Talat Xhaferi.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The election of Xhaferi was immediately met with protests led by VMRO-DPMNE, which was quickly handled by the police.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The early parliamentary elections took place on 15 July 2020.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Zoran Zaev has served as the prime minister of the Republic of North Macedonia again since August 2020.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Stevo Pendarovski was sworn in as North Macedonia's president in May 2019.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Prime minister Zoran Zaev announced his resignation after his party, the Social Democratic Union, suffered losses in local elections in October 2021.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In January 2022, Dimitar Kovačevski was elected as prime minister.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The new coalition cabinet composed of Kovačevski's Social Democrats and two ethnic Albanian parties.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Gordana Siljanovska-Davkova took office on 12 May 2024, becoming the country's first female president.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Parliament, or Assembly (Macedonian: Собрание, *Sobranie*), is the country's legislative body.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Constitution of North Macedonia has been in use since shortly after the independence of the republic in 1991.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] It limits the power of the governments, both local and national.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The military is also limited by the constitution.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The constitution states that North Macedonia is a social free state, and that Skopje is the capital.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The 120 members are elected for a mandate of four years through a general election.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Each citizen aged 18 years or older can vote for one of the political parties.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The current president of Parliament is Jovan Mitreski since 2024.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Executive power in North Macedonia is exercised by the Government, whose prime minister is the most politically powerful person in the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The members of the government are chosen by the prime minister and there are ministers for each branch of the society.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] There are ministers for economy, finance, information technology, society, internal affairs, foreign affairs and other areas.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The members of the Government are elected for a mandate of four years.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Judiciary power is exercised by courts, with the court system being headed by the Judicial Supreme court, Constitutional Court and the Republican Judicial Council.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia's statistical regions exist solely for legal and statistical purposes.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In August 2004, the country was reorganised into 84 municipalities (*opštini*; sing.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] *opština*) and reduced to 80 in 2013; 10 of the municipalities constitute the City of Skopje, a distinct unit of local self-government and the country's capital.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Most of the current municipalities were unaltered or merely amalgamated from the previous 123 municipalities established in September 1996; others were consolidated and their borders changed.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Prior to this, local government was organised into 34 administrative districts, communes, or counties (also opštini).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The use of the name "Macedonia" was disputed between Greece and North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The specific naming dispute was reignited after the breakup of Yugoslavia and the newly gained independence of the former Socialist Republic of Macedonia in 1991.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Greece opposed the use of the name without a geographical qualifier so as to avoid confusion with its own region of Greek Macedonia to the south.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The lower-cased "former" was chosen intentionally to display the provisionality of the name although most UN member countries soon abandoned the provisional reference and recognised the country as the *Republic of Macedonia* instead.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Most international organisations adopted the same convention along with over 100 UN members and four of the five permanent UN Security Council members.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In the period between 1991 and 2019, the country's name was an ongoing issue in bilateral and international relations.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The UN set up a negotiating process with a mediator, Matthew Nimetz, and the two parties to try to mediate the dispute.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Following the ratification of the Prespa agreement, most major international organisations welcomed the settlement of the long-standing dispute, and adopted the country's new name.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia became a member state of the UN on 8 April 1993, eighteen months after its independence from Yugoslavia, as "the former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia", and was referred as such within the UN until the 2019 resolution of the long-running dispute with Greece about the country's name.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The major interest of the country is a full integration in the European and the Trans-Atlantic integration processes.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In 2005, the country was officially recognised as a European Union candidate state.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] At the NATO 2008 Bucharest summit, Macedonia failed to gain an invitation to join the organisation because Greece vetoed the move after the dispute over the name issue.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The U.S. had previously expressed support for an invitation, but the summit then decided to extend an invitation only on condition of a resolution of the naming conflict with Greece.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In March 2009, the European Parliament expressed support for North Macedonia's EU candidacy and asked the EU Commission to grant the country a date for the start of accession talks by the end of 2009.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The parliament also recommended a speedy lifting of the visa regime for Macedonian citizens.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Prior to the Prespa agreement, the country failed to receive a start date for accession talks as a result of the naming dispute.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] However, after the Prespa agreement, North Macedonia became a member state of NATO on 27 March 2020.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The EU's stance was similar to NATO's in that resolution of the naming dispute was a precondition for the start of accession talks.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In October 2012, the EU Enlargement Commissioner Štefan Füle proposed a start of accession negotiations with the country for the fourth time, while the previous efforts were blocked each time by Greece.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] At the same time Füle visited Bulgaria in a bid to clarify the state's position with respect to Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] He established that Bulgaria had almost joined Greece in vetoing the accession talks.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Bulgarian position was that Sofia cannot grant an EU certificate to Skopje, which is systematically employing an ideology of hate towards Bulgaria.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Army of the Republic of North Macedonia (ARSM) is led by the General Staff.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Below it are the Operations Command, which includes the Mechanized Infantry Brigade, the Air Brigade, the Special Operations Regiment, and several independent battalions; the Training and Doctrine Command, which also oversees the Military Reserve Force; and the Logistics Base.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] There is also an Honor Guard Battalion that is directly subordinated to the General Staff.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] As of 2024 the ARSM had 8,000 active personnel and 4,850 reservists, and as of 2023 it had a military budget of US$275 million.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] It has been a volunteer military since conscription was ended in 2007.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia has deployed troops to Afghanistan, Bosnia and Herzegovina, Iraq, Kosovo, and Lebanon, as part of NATO, EU, or UN missions.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Ministry of Defence develops the Republic's defence strategy and assesses possible threats and risks.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] It is also responsible for the defence system, including training, readiness, equipment, and development, and for drawing up and presenting the defence budget.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia is a signatory to the European Convention on Human Rights and the UN Geneva Convention Relating to the Status of Refugees and Convention against Torture, and the Constitution guarantees basic human rights to all Macedonian citizens.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] According to human rights organisations, in 2003 there were suspected extrajudicial executions, threats against, and intimidation of, human rights activists and opposition journalists, and allegations of torture by the police.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Ranked as the fourth "best reformatory state" out of 178 countries ranked by the World Bank in 2009, North Macedonia has undergone considerable economic reform since independence.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The country has developed an open economy with trade accounting for more than 90% of GDP in recent years.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Since 1996, North Macedonia has witnessed steady, though slow, economic growth with GDP growing by 3.1% in 2005.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] This figure was projected to rise to an average of 5.2% in the 2006–2010 period.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The government has proven successful in its efforts to combat inflation, with an inflation rate of only 3% in 2006 and 2% in 2007, and has implemented policies focused on attracting foreign investment and promoting the development of small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The current government introduced a flat tax system with the intention of making the country more attractive to foreign investment.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The flat tax rate was 12% in 2007 and was further lowered to 10% in 2008. as of 2005 North Macedonia's unemployment rate was 37.2% and as of 2006 its poverty rate was 22%.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Due to a number of employment measures as well as the successful process of attracting multinational corporations, and according to the State Statistical Office of North Macedonia, the country's unemployment rate in the first quarter of 2015 decreased to 27.3%.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In terms of GDP structure, as of 2013, the manufacturing sector (including mining and construction) constituted the largest part of GDP at 21.4%, up from 21.1% in 2012.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The trade, transportation and accommodation sector represents 18.2% of GDP in 2013, up from 16.7% in 2012, while agriculture represents 9.6%, up from 9.1% in the previous year.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In terms of foreign trade, the largest sector contributing to the country's export in 2014 was "chemicals and related products" at 21.4%, followed by the "machinery and transport equipment" sector at 21.1%.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia's main import sectors in 2014 were "manufactured goods classified chiefly by material" with 34.2%, "machinery and transport equipment" with 18.7% and "mineral fuels, lubricants and related materials" with 14.4% of the total imports.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Even 68.8% of the foreign trade in 2014 was done with the EU which makes the Union by far the largest trading partner of North Macedonia (23.3% with Germany, 7.9% with the UK, 7.3% with Greece, 6.2% with Italy, etc.).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Almost 12% of the total external trade in 2014 was done with the Western Balkan countries.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In 2007, North Macedonia's information technology market increased 63.8% year on year, which was the fastest growing in the Adriatic region.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Corruption and a relatively ineffective legal system also act as significant restraints on successful economic development.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia still has one of the lowest per capita GDPs in Europe.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Furthermore, the country's grey market is estimated at close to 20% of GDP.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] PPS GDP per capita stood at 36% of the EU average in 2017.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] With a GDP per capita of US$9,157 at purchasing power parity and a Human Development Index of 0.701, North Macedonia is less developed and has a considerably smaller economy than most of the former Yugoslav states.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The outbreak of the Yugoslav wars and the imposition of sanctions on Serbia and Montenegro caused great damage to the country's economy, with Serbia constituting 60% of its markets before the disintegration of Yugoslavia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] When Greece imposed a trade embargo on the Republic in 1994–95, the economy was also affected.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Some relief was afforded by the end of the Bosnian War in November 1995 and the lifting of the Greek embargo, but the Kosovo War of 1999 and the 2001 Albanian crisis caused further destabilisation.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Since the end of the Greek embargo, Greece has become the country's most important business partner.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] (See Greek investments in North Macedonia.) Many Greek companies have bought former state companies in North Macedonia, such as the oil refinery Okta, the baking company Zhito Luks, a marble mine in Prilep, textile facilities in Bitola, etc., and employ 20,000 people.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The moving of business to North Macedonia in the oil sector has been caused by the rise of Greece in the oil markets.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Other key partners are Germany, Italy, the United States, Slovenia, Austria and Turkey.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Tourism plays a significant role in the economy of North Macedonia accounting for 6.7% of its GDP in 2016.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The annual income from tourism was estimated at 38.5 billion denars (€616 million) in that year.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Following its independence, the most serious negative impact on tourism performance occurred due to the armed conflicts taking place in 2001.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The number of foreign visitors has been on the rise since, with a 14.6% increase in 2011.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In 2019, North Macedonia received 1,184,963 tourist arrivals out of which 757,593 foreign.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Most numerous are tourists from Turkey, neighbouring Serbia, Greece and Bulgaria, Poland and other countries of Western Europe.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The biggest bulk of tourists, approximately 60% of the million tourists that visited the country in 2017, was situated in Skopje and the southwestern region of the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The most significant tourism branches are lake tourism as there are three lakes in Ohrid, Prespa and Dojran and over 50 small glacial lakes of variable sizes, mountainous tourism as there are 16 mountains higher than 2,000 metres.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Other forms of tourism also include rural and ecotourism, city tourism and cultural tourism, represented through gastronomy, traditional music, cultural celebrations and cultural heritage sites.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia (along with Montenegro, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Kosovo) belongs to the less-developed southern region of the former Yugoslavia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] It suffered severe economic difficulties after independence, when the Yugoslav internal market collapsed and subsidies from Belgrade ended.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In addition, it faced many of the same problems faced by other former socialist East European countries during the transition to a market economy.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Its main land and rail exports route, through Serbia, remains unreliable with high transit costs, thereby affecting the export of its formerly highly profitable, early vegetables market to Germany.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia is a landlocked country in the middle of the Balkan peninsula, and the main transport links in the country are those that connect the different parts of the peninsula (trans-Balkan links).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Particularly important is the connection between north–south and Vardar valley, which connects Greece with the rest of Europe.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] As of 2019, the total length of the railway network in North Macedonia was 922 km (573 mi).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Operated by Makedonski Železnici, the most important railway line is the line on the border with Serbia–Kumanovo–Skopje–Veles–Gevgelija–border with Greece.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Since 2001, the railway line Beljakovci has been built—the border with Bulgaria, which will get a direct connection Skopje-Sofia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The most important railway hub in the country is Skopje, while the other two are Veles and Kumanovo.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] As far as water transport is concerned, only lake traffic through Ohrid and Prespan Lake has been developed, mostly for tourist purposes.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] There are officially 17 airports in North Macedonia, of which 11 are with solid substrates.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Two are international airports: Skopje International Airport and Ohrid St.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia Post is the state-owned company for the provision of postal services.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] It was founded in 1992 as PTT Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In 1993 it was admitted to the World Postal Union.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In 1997, PTT Macedonia was divided into Macedonian Telekom and Macedonian Post (later renamed North Macedonia Post).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The United States Agency for International Development has underwritten a project called *Macedonia Connects*, which has made North Macedonia the first all-broadband wireless country in the world.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Ministry of Education and Sciences reports that 461 schools (primary and secondary) are now connected to the Internet.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In addition, an Internet service provider (On.net), has created a MESH Network to provide WIFI services in the 11 largest cities/towns in the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The results from the last 2021 census show a population of 1,836,713.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The population density of the country is 72.2 persons per km2 and the average age of the population is 40.08 years.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] 598,632 households were recorded with an average number of household members of 3.06.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The gender balance of the country is 50.4% female to 49.6% male.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Based on the 2021 census data, the largest ethnic group in the country are the ethnic Macedonians.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The second-largest group are the Albanians, who dominated much of the northwestern part of the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Following them, Turks are the third-biggest ethnic group of the country where official census data put them close to 70,000 and unofficial estimates suggest numbers between 170,000 and 200,000.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Some unofficial estimates indicate that there are possibly up to 260,000 Roma.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The national and official language in all aspects of the whole territory of North Macedonia and in its international relations is the Macedonian language.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Since 2019, Albanian is co-official at a state level (excluding defence, central police and monetary policy).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Macedonian belongs to the Eastern branch of the South Slavic language group, while Albanian occupies an independent branch of the Indo-European family of languages.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In municipalities where at least 20% of the population is part of another ethnic minority, those individual languages are used for official purposes in local government, alongside Macedonian and Albanian or just Macedonian.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Macedonian is closely related to and mutually intelligible with standard Bulgarian.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] It also has some similarities with standard Serbian and the intermediate Torlakian/Shop dialects spoken mostly in southeastern Serbia and western Bulgaria (and by speakers in the northeastern corner of the country).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The standard language was codified in the period following World War II and has accumulated a thriving literary tradition.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Besides Macedonian and Albanian, minority languages with substantial numbers of speakers are Turkish (including Balkan Gagauz), Romani, Serbian/Bosnian and Aromanian (including Megleno-Romanian).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Macedonian Sign Language is the primary language of those of the deaf community who did not pick up an oral language in childhood.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] According to the last census, 1,344,815 citizens of North Macedonia declared that they spoke Macedonian, 507,989 declared Albanian, 71,757 Turkish, 38,528 Romani, 24,773 Serbian, 8,560 Bosnian, 6,884 Aromanian and 19,241 spoke other languages.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Eastern Orthodox Christianity is the most practiced religion in North Macedonia, making up 46.1% of the population, the vast majority of whom belong to the Macedonian Orthodox Church.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Various other Christian denominations account for 13.9% of the population.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Muslims constitute 32.2% of the population.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia has the fifth-highest proportion of Muslims in Europe, after those of Kosovo (96%), Turkey (90%), Albania (59%), and Bosnia and Herzegovina (51%).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Most Muslims are Albanians, Turks, Romani or Bosniaks; few are Macedonian Muslims.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The remaining 1.4% was determined to be "unaffiliated" by a 2010 Pew Research estimation.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] There were 1,842 churches and 580 mosques in the country at the end of 2011.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Orthodox and Islamic religious communities have secondary religion schools in Skopje.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] There is an Orthodox theological college in the capital.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Macedonian Orthodox Church has jurisdiction over 10 provinces (seven in the country and three abroad), has 10 bishops and about 350 priests.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] A total of 30,000 people are baptised in all the provinces every year.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Macedonian Orthodox Church, which declared autocephaly in 1967, remained unrecognised by the other Orthodox Churches until 2022 when it restored relations with the Serbian Orthodox Church and the Ecumenical Patriarchate, which has been followed by recognition from other churches.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The reaction of the Macedonian Orthodox Church was to cut off all relations with the new Ohrid Archbishopric and to prevent bishops of the Serbian Orthodox Church from entering North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Bishop Jovan was jailed for 18 months for "defaming the Macedonian Orthodox church and harming the religious feelings of local citizens" by distributing Serbian Orthodox church calendars and pamphlets.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Macedonian Byzantine Catholic Church has approximately 11,000 adherents in North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Church was established in 1918, and is made up mostly of converts to Catholicism and their descendants.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The Church is of the Byzantine Rite and is in communion with the Roman and Eastern Catholic Churches.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Its liturgical worship is performed in Macedonian.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Former President Boris Trajkovski was a well-known Protestant.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] He was from the Methodist community, which is the largest and oldest Protestant church in the Republic, dating back to the late 19th century.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Since the 1980s the Protestant community has grown, partly through new confidence and partly with outside missionary help.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The country's Jewish community, which numbered some 7,200 people on the eve of World War II, was almost entirely destroyed during the war: only 2% survived the Holocaust.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] After their liberation and the end of the War, most opted to emigrate to Israel.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Today, the country's Jewish community numbers approximately 200 persons, almost all of whom live in Skopje.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Most Macedonian Jews are Sephardic—the descendants of 15th-century refugees who had been expelled from Castile, Aragon and Portugal.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The higher levels of education can be obtained at one of the five state universities: Ss.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Cyril and Methodius University of Skopje, St.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Clement of Ohrid University of Bitola, Goce Delčev University of Štip, State University of Tetova and University of Information Science and Technology "St.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] There are a number of private university institutions, such as the European University, Slavic University in Sveti Nikole, the South East European University and others.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia was ranked 63rd in the Global Innovation Index in 2025.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The national library of North Macedonia, National and University Library "St.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia has a rich cultural heritage in art, architecture, poetry and music.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] It has many ancient, protected religious sites.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Poetry, cinema, and music festivals are held annually.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Macedonian music styles developed under the strong influence of Byzantine church music.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia has a significant number of preserved Byzantine fresco paintings, mainly from the period between the 11th and 16th centuries.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] There are several thousands of square metres of fresco painting preserved, the major part of which is in very good condition and represent masterworks of the Macedonian school of ecclesiastical painting.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The most important cultural events in the country are the Ohrid Summer Festival of classical music and drama, the Struga Poetry Evenings which gather poets from more than 50 countries in the world, International Camera Festival in Bitola, Open Youth Theatre and Skopje Jazz Festival in Skopje etc.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The National Opera opened in 1947, then named "Macedonian Opera", with a performance of *Cavalleria rusticana* under the direction of Branko Pomorisac.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Every year, the May Opera Evenings are held in Skopje for around 20 nights.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The first May Opera performance was that of Kiril Makedonski's *Tsar Samuil* in May 1972.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The oldest newspaper in the country is *Nova Makedonija* from 1944.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Other well known newspaper and magazines are: *Utrinski vesnik*, *Dnevnik*, *Vest*, *Fokus*, *Večer*, *Tea Moderna*, *Makedonsko Sonce*, and *Koha*.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Public channel is Macedonian Radio Television founded in 1993 by the Assembly of North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] TEKO TV (1989) from Štip is the first private television channel in the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Other popular private channels are: Sitel, Kanal 5, Telma, Alfa TV, and Alsat-M.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The history of film making in the country dates back over 110 years.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The first film to be produced on the territory of the present-day country was made in 1895 by Janaki and Milton Manaki in Bitola.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Throughout the past century, the medium of film has depicted the history, culture and everyday life of the Macedonian people.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Over the years many Macedonian films have been presented at film festivals around the world and several of these films have won prestigious awards.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The first Macedonian feature film was *Frosina*, released in 1952 and directed by Vojislav Nanović.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The first feature film in colour was *Miss Stone*, a movie about a Protestant missionary in Ottoman Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The highest grossing feature film in North Macedonia was *Bal-Can-Can*, having been seen by over 500,000 people in its first year alone.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In 1994, Milcho Manchevski's film *Before the Rain* was nominated for an Academy Award in the category of Best International Feature Film.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Manchevski continues to be the most prominent modern filmmaker in the country having subsequently written and directed *Dust* and *Shadows*.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The country's cuisine is representative of that of the Balkans, incorporating Mediterranean and Middle Eastern (Ottoman), and to a lesser extent Italian, German and Eastern European (especially Hungarian) influences.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The relatively warm climate in North Macedonia provides excellent growth conditions for a variety of vegetables, herbs and fruits.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Macedonian cuisine contains a number dairy products, wines, and local alcoholic beverages, such as rakija.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Tavče gravče and mastika are the national dish and drink of North Macedonia, respectively.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Some other important dishes include Šopska salad, an appetiser and side dish that accompanies the main meal, ajvar, stuffed peppers, pastrmajlija and others.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Football, handball, and basketball are the most popular sports in North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The North Macedonia national football team is controlled by the Football Federation of Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Their home stadium is the Toše Proeski Arena.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In November 2003, to celebrate UEFA's jubilee, Darko Pančev was selected as the Golden Player of Macedonia as their most outstanding player of the past 50 years.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] He was the winner of the European Golden Boot award in 1991 and he is best known for scoring the winning penalty in the 1991 European Cup Final, bringing Red Star Belgrade the most prestigious trophy in European football for the first time in its 50-year existence.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In 2020, the national team qualified for UEFA Euro 2020 (held in 2021), their first major tournament in the country's history.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Handball is the other important team sport in the country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Macedonian clubs have enjoyed success in European competitions.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] RK Vardar won 2016–17 and 2018–19 EHF Champions League, while Kometal Gjorče Petrov Skopje won the 2002 EHF Women's Champions League.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The European Women's Handball Championship took place in 2008 in North Macedonia in Skopje and Ohrid; the women's national team finished seventh place.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The country's men's national team has appeared in the European and World championships multiple times, with a best finish of fifth at the former (2012) and ninth at the latter (2015).
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The North Macedonia national basketball team represents North Macedonia in international basketball.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] The team is run by the Basketball Federation of North Macedonia, the governing body of basketball in North Macedonia which was created in 1992 and joined FIBA in 1993.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia has participated in three EuroBaskets since then with its best finish at 4th place in 2011.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] It plays its home games at the Boris Trajkovski Sports Center in Skopje.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Pero Antić became the first Macedonian basketball player to play in the National Basketball Association.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] In the summer months the Ohrid Swimming Marathon is an annual event on Lake Ohrid and during the winter months there is skiing in North Macedonia's winter sports centres.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] North Macedonia also takes part in the Olympic Games.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Participation in the Games is organised by the Olympic Committee of North Macedonia.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Magomed Ibragimov competed for Macedonia in the freestyle 85 kg competition at the 2000 Summer Olympics and won the bronze medal, which was the first medal for independent country.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Wrestlers Shaban Trstena and Shaban Sejdiu born in North Macedonia, as well as boxers Redžep Redžepovski and Ace Rusevski, won Olympic medals as part of Yugoslav Olympic team.
[src:north-macedonia/north-macedonia-p02] Besides these, there are several major religious holidays and holidays of minorities.
[src:north-macedonia/мкд] The call started on 19 November 2012 and ended on 3 December 2012.
[src:north-macedonia/мкд] The Cyrillic domain proposal had to contain letters of the country's name.
[src:north-macedonia/мкд] On 3 December, MarNet chose six proposals (.мкд, .мак, .македонија, .рмкд, .рм and .рмак).
[src:north-macedonia/мкд] In the second phase of the process, citizens voted for the final Macedonian Cyrillic domain.
[src:north-macedonia/мкд] The winning proposal was officially announced in January 2013.
[src:north-macedonia/мкд] This also relates to the .mk domain, which is also owned by MARnet.
[src:north-macedonia/мкд] In the final phase of choosing the national Cyrillic domain, there were six domains.
[src:north-macedonia/мкд] During the voting period, 2,288 votes were registered and the final results were announced on the official MARnet website.
[src:north-macedonia/мкд] The domain .мкд was officially approved and registered on 20 March 2014.
